

## 🧠 Concept

* Array is **sorted but rotated**
* At least **one half is always sorted**
* Use this property to decide where to search

---

## ⚙️ Approach

* Find `mid`
* Check which side is sorted:

  * If `nums[mid] >= nums[si]` → left half is sorted
  * Else → right half is sorted
* Then check if target lies in the sorted half:

  * Yes → move inside that half
  * No → move to other half

---

## 💻 Code


class Solution {
    public int search(int[] nums, int target) {
        int n = nums.length;

        if (n == 1) {
            return (target == nums[0]) ? 0 : -1;
        }

        int si = 0;
        int ei = n - 1;

        while (si <= ei) {
            int mid = si + (ei - si) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] == target) {
                return mid;
            }

            // Left half sorted
            if (nums[mid] >= nums[si]) {
                if (target >= nums[si] && target < nums[mid]) {
                    ei = mid - 1;
                } else {
                    si = mid + 1;
                }
            }
            // Right half sorted
            else {
                if (target > nums[mid] && target <= nums[ei]) {
                    si = mid + 1;
                } else {
                    ei = mid - 1;
                }
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
}
```

---

## ⏱️ Complexity

* Time: `O(log n)`
* Space: `O(1)`

---

## 📌 Key Points

* One half is always sorted
* Use sorted half to decide direction
* No need to find pivot separately
* Works for all rotated cases

